The error you're seeing when type checking your JavaScript code with `checkJs` enabled is due to the fact that `this.serverUrl` seems to be an `Element`. In TypeScript and when type checking is active via `checkJs`, the type of a DOM element is `Element` by default, which does not have a `value` property. This is because `Element` is a base class for all elements, and not all of them have a `value` property (like `div` or `span` elements). The `value` property is specific to input elements (like `input`, `select`, etc.), which are more specifically typed as `HTMLInputElement`, `HTMLSelectElement`, etc.

To resolve this error, you need to inform the type checker that `this.serverUrl` is more specific than just an `Element`. Here's how to do it with a type assertion (commonly known as type casting):

```javascript
// Assuming `this.serverUrl` is an `HTMLInputElement`
this.ws = new WebSocket((this.serverUrl as HTMLInputElement).value);
```

Or, if you are writing in JavaScript (since `checkJs` is enabled) and want to stick with standard JavaScript without TypeScript-specific syntax, you can use JSDoc to type-cast:

```javascript
/** @type {HTMLInputElement} */
const inputElement = this.serverUrl;
this.ws = new WebSocket(inputElement.value);
```

Keep in mind that you should only perform this type assertion if you are certain that `this.serverUrl` will always be an input element. To guard against potential runtime errors if `this.serverUrl` is not the expected type, consider adding a runtime check:

```javascript
if (this.serverUrl instanceof HTMLInputElement) {
    this.ws = new WebSocket(this.serverUrl.value);
} else {
    // Handle the error appropriately
    console.error('serverUrl is not an input element');
}
```

Type assertions can be powerful, but they can also circumvent type safety if used improperly. Always ensure that your assertions are accurate to avoid potential runtime errors.

